# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: java-swing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] In computer programming, **event-driven programming** is a programming paradigm in which the flow of the program is determined by external events.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] User interface (UI) events from keyboards and mice, touchpads and touchscreens, and external sensor inputs are common cases.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] Events may also be programmatically generated, such as from messages from other programs, notifications from other threads, or other network events.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programming is the dominant paradigm used in graphical user interface (GUI) applications and network servers.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] In an event-driven application, there is generally an event loop that listens for events and then triggers a callback function when one of those events is detected.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programs can be written in any programming language, although the task is easier in languages that provide high-level abstractions.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] Although they do not exactly fit the event-driven model, interrupt handling and exception handling have many similarities.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] It is important to differentiate between event-driven and message-driven (aka queue-driven) paradigms: event-driven services (e.g.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] AWS SNS) are decoupled from their consumers, whereas message/queue-driven services (e.g.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] AWS SQS) are coupled with their consumers.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] Because the event loop that retrieves and dispatches events is common amongst applications, many programming frameworks provide an implementation of an event loop, and the application developer only needs to write the event handlers.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] The actual logic is contained in event handler routines.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] These routines handle the events to which the main program will respond.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] For example, a single mouse-click on a "Save" command button in a GUI program might trigger a routine to save data to a database.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] An "Exit" button might trigger a routine to exit the program.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] The event loop receives events from all such command buttons and other GUI elements, dispatching the appropriate event handler routine for each button.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] Event handler routines need to be bound to specific events, so the event loop can dispatch the correct routine in response to the event.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] Many IDEs simplify this process by providing the programmer with an event handling template for each specific event (such as a button click), allowing the programmer to focus on writing the event-handling code.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] In a sequential program, keeping track of execution order and history is normally trivial.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] But in an event-driven program, event handlers execute non-sequentially in response to external events.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] Special attention and planning is required to correctly structure the event handlers to work when called in any order.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] Most existing GUI architectures use event-driven programming.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] The Java AWT framework processes all UI changes on a single thread, called the Event dispatching thread.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] Similarly, all UI updates in the Java framework JavaFX occur on the JavaFX Application Thread.
[src:java-swing/event-driven-programming] Most network servers and frameworks such as Node.js are also event-driven.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] In software design, the **look and feel** of a graphical user interface comprises aspects of its design, including elements such as colors, shapes, layout, and typefaces (the "look"), as well as the behavior of dynamic elements such as buttons, boxes, and menus (the "feel").
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] The term can also refer to aspects of a non-graphical user interface (such as a command-line interface), as well as to aspects of an API – mostly to parts of an API that are not related to its functional properties.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] The term is used in reference to both software and websites.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] Look and feel applies to other products.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] In documentation, for example, it refers to the graphical layout (document size, color, font, etc.) and the writing style.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] In the context of equipment, it refers to consistency in controls and displays across a product line.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] Look and feel in operating system user interfaces serves two general purposes.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] First, it provides branding, helping to identify a set of products from one company.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] Second, it increases ease of use, since users will become familiar with how one product functions (looks, reads, etc.) and can translate their experience to other products with the same look and feel.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] Contrary to operating system user interfaces, for which look and feel is a part of the product identification, widget toolkits often allow users to specialize their application look and feel, by deriving the default look and feel of the toolkit, or by completely defining their own.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] This specialization can go from skinning (that only deals with the look, or visual appearance of the graphical control elements) to completely specializing the way the user interacts with the software (that is, the feel).
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] The definition of the look and feel to associate with the application is often done at initialization, but some Widget toolkits, such as the Swing widget toolkit that is part of the Java API, allow users to change the look and feel at runtime (see Pluggable look and feel).
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] Some companies try to assert copyright of trade dress over their look and feel.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] Unison* (1986) case was an early software copyright case that attempted to apply U.S. copyright law to the look and feel presented by a software product.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] In 1987 Lotus Development sued Paperback Software and Mosaic for copyright infringement, false and misleading advertising, and unfair competition over their low-cost clones of 1-2-3, VP Planner and Twin, and sued Borland over its Quattro spreadsheet.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] Dealers reported that sales of the clones increased because of publicity from the lawsuit.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] In December 1989, Xerox sued Apple over the Macintosh copyright.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] Apple Computer was notable for its use of the term *look and feel* in reference to their Mac OS operating system.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] The firm tried, with some success, to block other software developers from creating software that had a similar look and feel.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] Apple argued that they had a copyright claim on the look and feel of their software, and even went so far as to sue Microsoft, alleging that the Windows operating system was illegally copying their look and feel.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] ADAPSO could not come to a consensus on look and feel.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] The trade association's software products board of directors concluded that copyright should not protect look and feel.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] The software protection committee was so divided, however, that when Lotus's general counsel recused himself as chairman from a February 1987 meeting on the subject, the committee could not choose a replacement.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] Although provoking a vehement reaction from some in the software community, and causing Richard Stallman to form the League for Programming Freedom, the expected landmark ruling never happened, as most of the issues were resolved based on a license that Apple had granted Microsoft for Windows 1.0.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] The First Circuit Court of Appeals rejected a copyright claim on the feel of a user interface in *Lotus v.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] In 2012 and 2014, Apple Inc. filed lawsuits against competing manufacturers of smartphones and tablet computers, claiming that those manufacturers copied the look and feel of Apple's popular iPhone and iPad products.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] An API, which is an interface to software which provides some sort of functionality, can also have a certain look and feel.
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] Different parts of an API (e.g. different classes or packages) are often linked by common syntactic and semantic conventions (e.g. by the same asynchronous execution model, or by the same way object attributes are accessed).
[src:java-swing/look-and-feel] These elements are rendered either explicitly (i.e. are part of the syntax of the API), or implicitly (i.e. are part of the semantics of the API).
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:java-swing/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] The **Standard Widget Toolkit** (**SWT**) is a graphical widget toolkit for use with the Java platform.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] It was originally developed by Stephen Northover at IBM and is now maintained by the Eclipse Foundation in tandem with the Eclipse IDE.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] It is an alternative to the Abstract Window Toolkit (AWT) and Swing Java graphical user interface (GUI) toolkits provided by Sun Microsystems as part of the Java Platform, Standard Edition (J2SE).
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] To display GUI elements, the SWT implementation accesses the native GUI libraries of the operating system using Java Native Interface (JNI) in a manner that is similar to those programs written using operating system-specific application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Programs that call SWT are portable, but the implementation of the toolkit, despite part of it being written in Java, is unique for each platform.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] The toolkit is free and open-source software distributed under the Eclipse Public License, which is approved by the Open Source Initiative.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] The first Java GUI toolkit was the Abstract Window Toolkit (AWT), introduced with Java Development Kit (JDK) 1.0 as one component of Sun Microsystems' Java platform.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] The original AWT was a simple Java wrapper library around native (operating system-supplied) widgets such as menus, windows, and buttons.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Swing was the next generation GUI toolkit introduced by Sun in Java Platform, Standard Edition (J2SE) 1.2.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Swing was developed to provide a richer set of GUI software components than AWT.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Swing GUI elements are all-Java with no native code: instead of wrapping native GUI components, Swing draws its own components by using Java 2D to call low-level operating system drawing routines.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] The roots of SWT go back to work that Object Technology International (OTI), did in the 1990s when creating multiplatform, portable, native widget interfaces for Smalltalk, originally for OTI Smalltalk, which became IBM Smalltalk in 1993.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] IBM Smalltalk's Common Widget layer provided fast, native access to multiple platform widget sets while still providing a common API without suffering the *lowest common denominator* problem typical of other portable graphical user interface (GUI) toolkits.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] IBM was developing VisualAge, an integrated development environment (IDE) written in Smalltalk.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] They decided to open-source the project, which led to the development of Eclipse, intended to compete against other IDEs such as Microsoft Visual Studio.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Eclipse is written in Java, and IBM developers, deciding that they needed a toolkit that had "native look and feel" and "native performance", created SWT as a Swing replacement.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] SWT is a wrapper around native code objects, such as GTK objects, Motif objects etc.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Because of this, SWT widgets are often referred to as "heavyweight", evoking images of a light Java wrapper around a "heavy" native object.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] In cases where native platform GUI libraries do not support the functionality required for SWT, SWT implements its own GUI code in Java, similar to Swing.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] In essence, SWT is a compromise between the low-level performance and look and feel of AWT and the high-level ease of use of Swing.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] According to the Eclipse Foundation, "SWT and Swing are different tools that were built with different goals in mind.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] The purpose of SWT is to provide a common API for accessing native widgets across a spectrum of platforms.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] The primary design goals are high performance, native look and feel, and deep platform integration.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] It has been argued that SWT features a clean design, in part inspired by Erich Gamma of Design Patterns fame.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] SWT is a simpler toolkit than Swing, with less (possibly) extraneous functionality for the average developer.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] This has led some people to argue that SWT lacks functionality when compared to Swing.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Although SWT does not implement the popular model–view–controller (MVC) architecture used in Swing and multiple other high-level GUI toolkits, the JFace library, which is developed as part of the same Eclipse project, does provide a cross-platform, higher-level MVC abstraction atop SWT.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Developers may choose to use JFace to provide more flexible and abstract data models for complex SWT controls such as trees, tables, and lists, or access those controls directly as needed.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] SWT widgets have the same *look and feel* as native widgets because they often are the same native widgets.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] This is in contrast to the Swing toolkit where all widgets are emulations of native widgets.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] In some cases the difference is distinguishable.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] For example, the macOS tree widget features a subtle animation when a tree is expanded and default buttons have an animated pulsing glow to focus the user's attention on them.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] The default Swing version of these widgets does not animate.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Since SWT is simply a wrapper around native GUI code, it does not require large numbers of updates when that native code is changed, providing that operating system vendors are careful not to break clients of their API when the operating systems are updated.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] The same cannot be said of Swing, which supports the ability to change the look and feel of the running application with "pluggable looks and feels".
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] These enable emulating the native platform user interface using themes, which must be updated to mirror operating system GUI changes, such as theme or other look and feel updates.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] SWT aims for "deep platform integration", the Eclipse reference to SWT's use of native widgets.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] According to Mauro Marinillia of developer.com, "whenever one needs a tight integration with the native platform, SWT can be a plus".
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] This deep integration can be useful in a number of ways, for example enabling SWT to wrap ActiveX objects on Microsoft Windows.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] The following is a basic "Hello, World!" program using SWT.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] It shows a window (*Shell*) and a label.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Contrary to Swing, a *Display* class is necessary to access the underlying operating system, and its resources must be explicitly disposed of when they are no longer used.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] SWT must be ported to every new GUI library that needs supporting.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Unlike Swing and AWT, SWT is not available on every Java-supported platform since SWT is not part of the Java release.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] There is also some evidence that the performance of SWT on platforms other than Windows is noticeably less efficient.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Since SWT uses a different native library for each platform, SWT programs may be exposed to platform-specific bugs.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] SWT exposes programs to more low-level details than Swing.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Since the SWT implementation is different for each platform, a platform-specific SWT library (JAR file) must be distributed with each application.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Windows XP has historically been supported, as have Linux on s390, Solaris 11 (SPARCv9), Solaris 10 (x86_64), HP-UX (ia64), and AIX (PPC and PPC64).
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] SWT was designed to be a *high performance* GUI toolkit; faster, more responsive and lighter on system resource usage than Swing.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] There has been some attempted benchmarking of SWT and Swing, which concluded that SWT should be more efficient than Swing, although the applications benchmarked in this case were not complex enough to draw solid conclusions for all possible SWT or Swing uses.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] A fairly thorough set of benchmarks concluded that neither Swing nor SWT outperformed the other in the general case.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Due to the use of native code, SWT classes do not allow for easy inheritance for all widget classes, which some users consider can hurt extensibility.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] This can make customizing existing widgets more difficult to achieve with SWT than if one were using Swing.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Both toolkits support writing new widgets using only Java code, however in SWT extra work is needed to make the new widget work on every platform.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] SWT widgets, unlike almost any other Java toolkit, requires manual object deallocation, in contrast to the standard Java practice of automatic garbage collection.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] SWT objects must be explicitly deallocated using the `dispose` method, which is analogous to the C language's `free`.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] If this is not done, memory leaks or other unintended behavior may result.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] On this matter, some have commented that "explicitly de-allocating the resources could be a step back in development time (and costs) at least for the average Java developer" and that "this is a mixed blessing.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] It means more control (and more complexity) for the SWT developer instead of more automation (and slowness) when using Swing." The need for manual object deallocation when using SWT is largely due to SWT's use of native objects.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] These objects are not tracked by the Java JVM, so it cannot track whether or not such objects are in use, and thus cannot garbage collect them at a suitable time.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] There is some development activity to enable combining Swing and SWT.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Starting in 2006, there was an SWT-3.2 port to the programming language D called DWT.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Since then, the project supports Windows 32-bit, and Linux GTK 32-bit for SWT-3.4.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] The DWT project also has an addon package that contains a port of JFace and Eclipse Forms.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] With JavaFX becoming part of the Java SE platform there has been interest in developing a backend for SWT that relies on JavaFX in a similar way to SWTSwing relies on Swing.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] A prominent project trying to achieve that was *SWT on JavaFX* which became part of *e(fx)clipse* in 2014.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Recent open-source efforts in the Eclipse community have led to a porting of SWT (and JFace) into a widget toolkit appropriate for the web.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] The result has been the Eclipse Remote Application Platform (RAP), which combines the qooxdoo Ajax library with the SWT API.
[src:java-swing/standard-widget-toolkit] Like other Java Ajax projects (such as Echo2, Vaadin and Google Web Toolkit), the usage of the SWT API allows developing applications quickly for the web in much the same way as for the desktop.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Swing was developed to provide a more sophisticated set of GUI components than the earlier Abstract Window Toolkit (AWT).
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Swing provides a look and feel that emulates the look and feel of several platforms, and also supports a pluggable look and feel that allows applications to have a look and feel unrelated to the underlying platform.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] It has more powerful and flexible components than AWT.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] In addition to familiar components such as buttons, check boxes and labels, Swing provides several advanced components such as tabbed panel, scroll panes, trees, tables, and lists.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Unlike AWT components, Swing components are not implemented by platform-specific code.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Instead, they are written entirely in Java and therefore are platform-independent.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] In December 2008, Sun Microsystems (Oracle's predecessor) released the CSS / FXML based framework that it intended to be the successor to Swing, called JavaFX.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The Internet Foundation Classes (IFC) were a graphics library for Java originally developed by Netscape Communications Corporation and first released on December 16, 1996.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] On April 2, 1997, Sun Microsystems and Netscape Communications Corporation announced their intention to incorporate IFC with other technologies to form the Java Foundation Classes.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Swing introduced a mechanism that allowed the look and feel of every component in an application to be altered without making substantial changes to the application code.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The introduction of support for a pluggable look and feel allows Swing components to emulate the appearance of native components while still retaining the benefits of platform independence.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Originally distributed as a separately downloadable library, Swing has been included as part of the Java Standard Edition since release 1.2.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The Swing classes and components are contained in the `javax.swing` package hierarchy.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Development of Swing's successor, JavaFX, started in 2005, and it was officially introduced two years later at JavaOne 2007.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] JavaFX was open-sourced in 2011 and, in 2012, it became part of the Oracle JDK download.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] JavaFX is replacing Swing owing to several advantages, including being more lightweight, having CSS styling, sleek design controls, and the use of FXML and Scene Builder.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] In 2018, JavaFX was made a part of the OpenJDK under the OpenJFX project to increase the pace of its development.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Members of the Java Client team that was responsible for Swing included James Gosling (Architect), Rick Levenson (manager), Amy Fowler & Hans Muller (co-technical leads), Tom Ball, Jeff Dinkins, Georges Saab, Tim Prinzing, Jonni Kanerva, and Jeannette Hung & Jim Graham (2D Graphics).
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Swing is a platform-independent, "model–view–controller" GUI framework for Java, which follows a single-threaded programming model.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Additionally, this framework provides a layer of abstraction between the code structure and graphic presentation of a Swing-based GUI.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Swing is platform-independent because it is completely written in Java.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Complete documentation for all Swing classes can be found in the Java API Guide for Version 6 or the Java Platform Standard Edition 8 API Specification for Version 8.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Swing is a **component-based framework**, whose components are all ultimately derived from the `JComponent` class.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Swing objects asynchronously fire events, have bound properties, and respond to a documented set of methods specific to the component.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Swing components are JavaBeans components, compliant with the JavaBeans specification.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Swing's heavy reliance on runtime mechanisms and indirect composition patterns allows it to respond at run time to fundamental changes in its settings.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] For example, a Swing-based application is capable of hot swapping its user-interface during runtime.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Furthermore, users can provide their own look and feel implementation, which allows for uniform changes in the look and feel of existing Swing applications without any programmatic change to the application code.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Swing's high level of flexibility is reflected in its inherent ability to override the native host operating system (OS)'s GUI controls for displaying itself.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Swing "paints" its controls using the Java 2D APIs, rather than calling a native user interface toolkit.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Thus, a Swing component does not have a corresponding native OS GUI component, and is free to render itself in any way that is possible with the underlying graphics GUIs.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] However, at its core, every Swing component relies on an AWT container, since (Swing's) `JComponent` extends (AWT's) Container.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] This allows Swing to plug into the host OS's GUI management framework, including the crucial device/screen mappings and user interactions, such as key presses or mouse movements.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Swing simply "transposes" its own (OS-agnostic) semantics over the underlying (OS-specific) components.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] So, for example, every Swing component paints its rendition on the graphic device in response to a call to component.paint(), which is defined in (AWT) Container.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] But unlike AWT components, which delegated the painting to their OS-native "heavyweight" widget, Swing components are responsible for their own rendering.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] This transposition and decoupling is not merely visual, and extends to Swing's management and application of its own OS-independent semantics for events fired within its component containment hierarchies.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Generally speaking, the Swing architecture delegates the task of mapping the various flavors of OS GUI semantics onto a simple, but generalized, pattern to the AWT container.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Building on that generalized platform, it establishes its own rich and complex GUI semantics in the form of the `JComponent` model.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The Swing library makes heavy use of the model–view–controller software design pattern, which conceptually decouples the data being viewed from the user interface controls through which it is viewed.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Because of this, most Swing components have associated *models* (which are specified in terms of Java interfaces), and the programmers can use various default implementations or provide their own.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The framework provides default implementations of model interfaces for all of its concrete components.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The typical use of the Swing framework does not require the creation of custom models, as the framework provides a set of default implementations that are transparently, by default, associated with the corresponding `JComponent` child class in the Swing library.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] In general, only complex components, such as tables, trees and sometimes lists, may require the custom model implementations around the application-specific data structures.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] To get a good sense of the potential that the Swing architecture makes possible, consider the hypothetical situation where custom models for tables and lists are wrappers over DAO and/or EJB services.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Typically, Swing component model objects are responsible for providing a concise interface defining events fired, and accessible properties for the (conceptual) data model for use by the associated JComponent.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] For example, the `JTable` has a model called `TableModel` that describes an interface for how a table would access tabular data.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] A default implementation of this operates on a two-dimensional array.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The view component of a Swing JComponent is the object used to graphically represent the conceptual GUI control.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] A distinction of Swing, as a GUI framework, is in its reliance on programmatically rendered GUI controls (as opposed to the use of the native host OS's GUI controls).
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Prior to Java 6 Update 10, this distinction was a source of complications when mixing AWT controls, which use native controls, with Swing controls in a GUI (see Mixing AWT and Swing components).
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Finally, in terms of visual composition and management, Swing favors relative layouts (which specify the positional relationships between components) as opposed to absolute layouts (which specify the exact location and size of components).
[src:java-swing/swing-java] This bias towards "fluid"' visual ordering is due to its origins in the applet operating environment that framed the design and development of the original Java GUI toolkit.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Since early versions of Java, a portion of the Abstract Window Toolkit (AWT) has provided platform-independent APIs for user interface components.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] In AWT, each component is rendered and controlled by a native peer component specific to the underlying windowing system.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] By contrast, Swing components are often described as *lightweight* because they do not require allocation of native resources in the operating system's windowing toolkit.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The AWT components are referred to as *heavyweight components*.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Much of the Swing API is generally a complementary extension of the AWT rather than a direct replacement.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] In fact, every Swing lightweight interface ultimately exists within an AWT heavyweight component because all of the top-level components in Swing (`JApplet`, `JDialog`, `JFrame`, and `JWindow`) extend an AWT top-level container.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Prior to Java 6 Update 10, the use of both lightweight and heavyweight components within the same window was generally discouraged due to Z-order incompatibilities.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] However, later versions of Java have fixed these issues, and both Swing and AWT components can now be used in one GUI without Z-order issues.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The core rendering functionality used by Swing to draw its lightweight components is provided by Java 2D, another part of JFC.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The Standard Widget Toolkit (SWT) is a competing toolkit originally developed by IBM and now maintained by the Eclipse community.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] SWT's implementation has more in common with the heavyweight components of AWT.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] This confers benefits such as more accurate fidelity with the underlying native windowing toolkit, at the cost of an increased exposure to the native platform in the programming model.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] A fairly thorough set of benchmarks in 2005 concluded that neither Swing nor SWT clearly outperformed the other in the general case.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The first **`import`** includes all the public classes and interfaces from the **`javax.swing`** package.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The `**Hello**` class `**extends**` the **`JFrame`** class; the `JFrame` class implements a window with a title bar and a close control.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The `**Hello()**` constructor initializes the frame by first calling the superclass constructor, passing the parameter `"Hello World"`, which is used as the window's title.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Next, a **`JLabel`** is created for the string **"Hello, world!"** and the **`add(Component)`** method inherited from the `Container` superclass is called to add the label to the frame.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The **`pack()`** method inherited from the `Window` superclass is called to size the window and lay out its contents.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The **`setVisible(boolean)`** method inherited from the `Component` superclass is called with the Boolean parameter `**true**`, which causes the frame to be displayed.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The `**main()**` method is called by the Java virtual machine when the program starts.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] It instantiates a new **`Hello`** frame.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The code uses the **`invokeLater(Runnable)`** method to invoke the constructor from the AWT event dispatching thread in order to ensure the code is executed in a thread-safe manner.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Once the frame is displayed, exiting the `main` method does not cause the program to terminate because the event dispatching thread remains active until all of the Swing top-level windows have been disposed.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The following is a rather simple Swing-based program.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] It displays a window (a `JFrame`) containing a label and a button.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Notice how all instantiation and handling of Swing components are done by implementing the Runnable interface.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] This is then run on the Event Dispatch Thread by use of the method `SwingUtilities.invokeLater(Runnable)`), created in the main method (see Swing and thread safety).
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Text fields enable users to input text or data into your application.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Creating a text field in Swing is straightforward – instantiate a JTextField object and add it to a container.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Enhancing functionality in text fields improves user interaction.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] By attaching DocumentListener interfaces, you can dynamically monitor changes in the text content, enabling real-time validation, formatting, or auto-completion of input data.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Validating text field input is crucial for ensuring data integrity and preventing errors.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Swing provides multiple validation techniques, including regular expressions, input masks, or custom validation logic.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] By implementing InputVerifier interfaces, you can define specific validation rules and offer immediate feedback to users when input is invalid.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] In this example let javax.swing.JFrame be super class and add our own widget(s) to it (in this case, a JButton).
[src:java-swing/swing-java] The layout is set to null using the `Container.setLayout(LayoutManager)` method since JFrame uses java.awt.BorderLayout as its default layout-manager.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] With BorderLayout anything which is added to the container is placed in the center and stretched to accommodate any other widgets.
[src:java-swing/swing-java] Most real world GUI applications would prefer to use a layout-manager instead of placing everything on absolute co-ordinates.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] In a graphical user interface (GUI), a **graphical widget** (also **graphical control element** or **control**) is an element of interaction, such as a button or a scroll bar.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] Controls are software components that a computer user interacts with through direct manipulation to read or edit information about an application.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] User interface libraries such as Windows Presentation Foundation, Qt, GTK, and Cocoa, contain a collection of controls and the logic to render these.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] Each widget facilitates a specific type of user-computer interaction, and appears as a visible part of the application's GUI as defined by the theme and rendered by the rendering engine.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] The theme makes all widgets adhere to a unified aesthetic design and creates a sense of overall cohesion.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] Some widgets support interaction with the user, for example labels, buttons, and check boxes.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] Others act as containers that group the widgets added to them, for example windows, panels, and tabs.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] Structuring a user interface with widget toolkits allows developers to reuse code for similar tasks, and provides users with a common language for interaction, maintaining consistency throughout the whole information system.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] Graphical user interface builders facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] They automatically generate all the source code for a widget from general descriptions provided by the developer, usually through direct manipulation.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] Around 1920, *widget* entered American English, as a generic term for any useful device, particularly a product manufactured for sale; a gadget.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] In 1988, the term *widget* is attested in the context of Project Athena and the X Window System.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] The same year, in the manual *X Toolkit Widgets - C Language X Interface* by Ralph R.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] Finally, still in the same year, Ralph R.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] Any widget displays an information arrangement changeable by the user, such as a window or a text box.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] The defining characteristic of a widget is to provide a single interaction point for the direct manipulation of a given kind of data.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] In other words, widgets are basic visual building blocks which, combined in an application, hold all the data processed by the application and the available interactions on this data.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] GUI widgets are graphical elements used to build the human-machine-interface of a program.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] GUI widgets are implemented like software components.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] Widget toolkits and software frameworks, like e.g.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] GTK+ or Qt, contain them in software libraries so that programmers can use them to build GUIs for their programs.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] A family of common reusable widgets has evolved for holding general information based on the Palo Alto Research Center Inc. research for the Xerox Alto User Interface.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] Various implementations of these generic widgets are often packaged together in widget toolkits, which programmers use to build graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] Most operating systems include a set of ready-to-tailor widgets that a programmer can incorporate in an application, specifying how it is to behave.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] Each type of widget generally is defined as a class by object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] Therefore, many widgets are derived from class inheritance.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] In the context of an application, a widget may be *enabled* or *disabled* at a given point in time.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] An enabled widget has the capacity to respond to events, such as keystrokes or mouse actions.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] A widget that cannot respond to such events is considered disabled.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] The appearance of a widget typically differs depending on whether it is enabled or disabled; when disabled, a widget may be drawn in a lighter color ("**grayed out**") or be obscured visually in some way.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] On pop-up dialogues, buttons might appear greyed out shortly after appearance to prevent accidental clicking or inadvertent double-tapping.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] Widgets are sometimes qualified as *virtual* to distinguish them from their physical counterparts, e.g.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] *virtual* buttons that can be clicked with a pointer, vs. physical buttons that can be pressed with a finger (such as those on a computer mouse).
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] A related (but different) concept is the desktop widget, a small specialized GUI application that provides some visual information and/or easy access to frequently used functions such as clocks, calendars, news aggregators, calculators and desktop notes.
[src:java-swing/widget-gui] These kinds of widgets are hosted by a widget engine.
